\begin_layout Itemize
My first goal is to focus on spin-outs.
 The tradeoffs are:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Bad for welfare: 
\series default
Non-competes prevent some employees from starting socially efficient firms.
 We might want these startups because:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Employee has a new idea that for some reason can't be implemented by his
 current firm (e.g.
 he has no way of communicating the value of the idea without revealing
 it to his employer, as in Esteban's paper on spinoffs and the market for
 ideas)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Good and/or bad for welfare: 
\series default
Non-competes allow a firm with some monopoly power to keep that monopoly
 power.
 This has good and bad effects:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This 
\emph on
reduces static efficiency 
\emph default
or 
\emph on
ex-post efficiency 
\emph default
- there may be underprovision of the good / service due to monopoly power
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But 
\emph on
enhances dynamic efficiency
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
ex-ante efficiency 
\emph default
- if monopoly power is based on being the only firm with certain productivity-re
levant knowledge which cost resources to create, then solidifying this monopoly
 could, ex ante, increase efficiency, by internalizing the returns to R&D
 effort, thus incentivizing the production of this knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Good and/or bad for welfare: 
\series default
creative destruction.
 The level of non-compete enforcement determines the expected length of
 a monopoly upon a successful innovation.
 This applies to the person who 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

creates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the good category, as well as subsequent innovations that improve on it
 (and steal the original inventor's business).
 However, those later innovations involve some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

business stealing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: with full knowledge spillovers (free entry into innovation race, common
 in most endogenous growth models), there can easily be too much innovation
 by entrants in equilibrium, since their private benefits from success are
 larger than the social benefits.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Note: 
\series default
caveats re: optimal contracting
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The above says: ex post, a restriction on competition has the above effects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
However, optimal contracting could dull some negative effects of non-compete
 enforcement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Buyout clauses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
