\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
However, the solutions above (e.g.
 buyout clauses) are not used in practice, so I focus on a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vanilla
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 non-compete contract with no non-compete clause (and no opportunity for
 negotiation, since this also does not occur).
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
One reason why buyouts do not occur in practice for spinouts by R&D workers
 is financial frictions - such workers are unable to pledge future earnings
 to finance the buyout â€“ see Rauch 2015.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rauch depends on the firm 
\emph on
requiring full compensation 
\emph default
for the non-compete to be bought out.
 Alternatively, could have contracts as in Shi 2017, which allow the firm
 to commit to a price for buying out the non-compete in different verifiable
 states of the world.
 This might allow the firm to privatize some of the benefits of their innovation
, while still committing to allowing the employee to start up any truly
 attractive ventures (which is a way for the firm to indirectly compensate
 the employee).
 But this also does not occur in practice.
 Why this does not occur is outside the scope of this paper, but it could
 be because the costs of making these negotiations are too difficult, or
 because of some adverse selection problem or other market failure.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This increases tractability, but has the potential to bias results.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Non-compete contracts in the model are extra restrictive.
 Given parameters and enforcement level, we are farther away from competition.
 Given that we estimate the model based on measures of competition, this
 will bias parameters towards those that create more competition given level
 of non-compete enforcement.
 This is not explained well, but the ponit is results could be biased.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Note: 
\series default
caveats re: synthetic non-competes.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In a non-enforcing region, a firm could conceivably pay an employee a high
 wage to prevent them from opening up a firm that would harm the incumbent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The firm will optimally do this as long as the value to the worker of opening
 up the new firm is less than or equal to the damage caused to the firm
 from the worker opening up the firm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is exactly the cases in which it is socially optimal for the spinoff
 not to occur.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consequently, when this is possible, non-compete agreements are not even
 required to prevent creative destruction from eating away all joint monopoly
 profits.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead, they serve a different purpose: they allow the firm to insure the
 workers against this risk.
 Instead of structuring the workers payments as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low wage + large raise / implicit payout if they are lucky enough to learn
 how to compete against the company
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, they structure them as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

medium wage no matter what
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: if the worker learns how to compete, they are either not willing to pay
 the buyout clause (because their idea does not improve bilateral joint
 value), or they do buy out the clause, which transfers their surplus to
 the firm.
 The firm does not care either way - in expected present value terms, they
 have still internalized the profits from their original R&D.
 But the worker may be better off if risk averse, which would allow the
 firm to pay them less in expectation, holding the worker's utility constant
 - a Pareto improvement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Need to think more about whether the above makes any sense.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How to estimate the model?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Observability of non-compete contracts: 
\series default
we do not observe non-compete contracts in the data.
 Throughout, I simply assume that jobs in enforcing regions have non-compete
 contracts and jobs in non-enforcing regions do not.
 This has the potential to bias results, as noted above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Naive approach:
\series default
 Identify based on the cross section of states.
 Compare outcomes in states which do enforce to outcomes in states which
 do not enforce.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Problem: 
\series default
many other (unmeasured, unmodeled) differences in fundamentals could be
 causing the differences in outcomes 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
By doing diff-in-diff-in-diff methodologies, can somewhat fix this.
 Sure, we might expect state A to be better than state B for random other
 reasons, but do we expect it to be particularly better than state B for
 a certain industry? This is the strategy in Balasubramaniam et al.
 2017.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Problem: 
\series default
even if the effect is causally related to non-compete enforcement, it could
 be due to things shifting across states.
 Need to control for this.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Slightly less naive approach: 
\series default
Identify based on the result of an exogenous change in policy
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We get rid of Problem 1 above, since we isolate a *change* in one policy.
 Essentially, we difference out state-effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We still have Problem 2, however - even if a state 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

does better
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

does worse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 after a unilateral policy change, this could be due to the presence of
 other states.
 Maybe enforcement leads to massive brain drain, as happened when Michigan
 started enforcing.
 Need to account for contribution of these channels.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
My approach: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
As described above, eliminate Problem 1 by various means.
 Either triple-diff stuff, or focusing on random experiments.
 In this way, we come up with a bunch of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

identified moments
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that we want our macro model to reproduce
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
E.g., we come up with a bunch of numbers from the data which correspond to
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what would happen if I exogenously change this policy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the model.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Eliminate Problem 2 by having a model which can account for the contribution
 of these cross-state spillover channels.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Essentially, the model needs to have all of the relevant channels in the
 data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One of these channels is cross-state migration of talented inventors and
 entrepreneurs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We either measure this channel directly (hard, since I don't observe everything)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Or (and this is my preferred method), have a model of the location decision
 of all relevant agents, which has certain common parameters in it, and
 calibrate those parameters to match the relocation decisions that we 
\emph on
do 
\emph default
observe.
 Essentially, extrapolating in a model-disciplined way.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Once we have done this, we can actually use these identified moments to
 estimate the parameters governing the non-compete enforcement tradeoff
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Essentially: do non-enforcing states do 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

well enough
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relative to how we think they would do given their demographics; does a
 state do 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worse enough
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 after changing its enforcement relative to how we think it would do based
 on the brain drain this causes, to give us evidence that this policy change
 would have been bad in a closed economy?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
